definitions.definition: ( transitive and intransitive ) To move gently back and forth .
examples: The empty swing rocked back and forth in the wind.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To cause to shake or sway violently.
( intransitive ) To sway or tilt violently back and forth.
( transitive and intransitive , of ore etc. ) To be washed and panned in a cradle or in a rocker .
examples: The ores had been rocked and laid out for inspection.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To disturb the emotional equilibrium of; to distress ; to greatly impact (most often positively).
examples: Downing Street has been rocked by yet another sex scandal.

definitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To do well or to be operating at high efficiency .
( slang , ambitransitive , euphemistic ) To make love to or have sex (with).
( intransitive ) To sway one's body as a stim .

definitions.definition: To play, perform, or enjoy rock music, especially with a lot of skill or energy.
To be very favourable or skilful ; excel ; be fantastic .
examples: My holidays in Ibiza rocked ! I can't wait to go back.

definitions.definition: To thrill or excite , especially with rock music.
To have people dancing and enjoying rock music.
To do something with excitement yet skillfully.
examples: I need to rock a piss.

definitions.definition: To wear (a piece of clothing, outfit etc.) successfully or with style; to carry off (a particular look, style).
